mber 16, 2006 and has been extended every 30 days since then. On May 16, 2007 the Emergency Powers Regulations 2006 was replaced by the new Emergency Powers Regulations 2007, which removed some powers that were given to the TPF and TDS under the old regulation (see example 4). The political situation in Tonga is still affected by the fallout from these riots. A 2007 report by a community task force on human rights revealed that 41% of individuals arrested since the riots experienced violence during their arrest, reportedly perpetrated by the TDS. Many claimed to have been interviewed with violence or intimidation and all reported overcrowded and unhealthy prison conditions.143 In addition, during the riots the integrity and image of the police force was damaged due to it being seen as unprepared to deal with such an extraordinary event. However, it should be noted that based on the evidence and complaints so far, the alleged unlawful actions were not widespread or an organised misuse of power. There was also glaring evidence that if the police had not called for the assistance of the TDS, the rioters would have done more destruction to the capital.144 In 2008 the Legislative Assembly passed the Constitution and Electoral Commission Act, with the commission given ten months to submit a report and recommendations to the Privy Council and the Legislative Assembly. It is then up to the Privy Council to reject or accept the recommendations. With the deadline for public submissions closed, twenty-nine written submissions had been received.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7864310a-f0bb-44ee-8673-4733f350c390": {"__data__": {"id_": "7864310a-f0bb-44ee-8673-4733f350c390", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/enhancing-security-sector-governance-pacific-region-strategic-fr